orthwestern Europe during World War II. In an effort to secure this data, the German Navy and Air Force secretly established manned weather stations in East Greenland, Svalbard, and Franz Josef Land. War North of 80: The Last German Arctic Weather Station of World War II is the personal story of Wilhelm Dege, the leader of the last weather station, code-named "Operation Haudegen." With a detailed introduction, Barr's translation offers Engish-speaking readers a rare glimpse into the Germans' account of weather activities during World War II in the Arctic. An epilogue written by Dege's son offers insight into the various fates of the expedition members who worked alongside his father.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMeteorological stationszNorwayzSvalbardxHistory. 0aMeteorologistszGermanyvBiography. 0aMilitary meteorologyzArctic regionsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitary meteorologyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, German. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zNorwayzSvalbard. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh1 aBarr, William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552384749?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552384749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552384749/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles